r Eleanor, her court, and her family. Moshé Lazar reexamines her relationship to the courtly-love literature of the period. Eleanor S. Greenhill and Larry M. Ayres reassess her influence in the realm of art history. Rossell Hope Robbins traces the lines extending from the French courtly literature of Eleanor's period down into fourteenth-century Chaucerian England. The essays reflect divergent but generally complementary assessments of this remarkable woman's influence on her own era and on future times as well. This volume is the result of a symposium held at the University of Texas in 1973.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aQueenszFrancexBiographyvCongresses. 0aQueenszGreat BritainxBiographyvCongresses. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh1 aAyres, Larry M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaltzer, Rebecca A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Elizabeth A. R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreenhill, Eleanor S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKibler, William W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKibler, William W., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLazar, Moshé, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRobbins, Rossell Hope, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477300237423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477300237/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK